annotation: Van't Kuijs opening (A00) is a opening that does not give out central control. (For anyone that does this opening: You can still play it but you have to perform an entire opening sequence that helps you gain control of e4d4 e5 d5.)
best opening move performed by black
I didn't like this move and the reason is that your opponent wouldn't magically play the f-pawn on their second move. It is suicidal.
Tackles the bishop's line.
The usual knight developement. A correct play.
The play is even with nothing to risk.
White played a ridiculous move that wastes time. The correct move was 4.d4.
I didn't like this move too much. 4...d5 was a better opportunity for advancement
White decided to mess up my ability to castle on his next move or probably had his knight tempt my queen (which is not going to happen).
I spotted 6.Nf7 but it isn't really necessary. Better was 5...Ne5!.
Still trying to attain my Queen or Rook White played this and forgot about 1. his position and 2. my knight.
I forked his Bishop and his Queen so he hurried to move his Queen and forgot about my knight completely.
?. 7.Qe2 was correct.
! Knight and Bishop sacrificed to attain Black's Queen.
I tried to tempt White by this move.
?! Does White understand what he is doing? Dubious pawn push.
!? Risky but well worth considering. I tried to stop White's h-pawn and with this move there is only one way to kill his pawn. If 11. h6 It is a wasted move.
The pawn is trapped and White is forced to find strong developement options or he will slowly crumble.
Castled to protect f7-pawn with the rook
With this move White decide to try to sacrifice a bishop to obtain my rook. The structure of the move is poor.
I demolish White's plan with this attack to crush White's rook.
?. Clearly White now has several problem to control. Correct play is 13.Nc3.
A crazy knight move.
Good response but the knight was underestimated again!
I begin my second assault with this take. Both sides have an attacked knight!
White's knight is safe.
?!. I completely forgot about 15...Nf3+!.
A premature attack that forces my King to h8.
An okay move; White has to be really careful about his next move
Giving up the c1-a3 diagonal White gave up c1 thus giving me a free rook.
White exposed my King to his Bishop and still hung on to his h6-pawn which is not a good option for him.
A clumsy King move. 21.Na3 is a smarter move.
Better is 21...Qxg2.
White begins to annoy me with checks but he lacks material to do so.
A move that sends the Rook to g8
White's h-pawn is prepared to promote
White is only push my Rook to strategic locations
?? Blunder. Better was 27...Re8
Unbelievable!!! White ignored 28.h8=Q and decided to do this weak move. Realizing that he'll spot this I hurried to move my Rook to e8.
White did a weird move.
I begin to develope the rest of my pieces.
Forget 30...Qe4+? I was aiming for long distance check.
To the least interest for me his pieces are still well guarded.
31...Bd5 was better. At least this move helped me get something back.
White is losing material because of his failed pawn pass.
Another block. This time the annoying and brutal knight is preventing me from doing something good.
I sacrifice my bishop...
and recieved a way to destroy White's position.
I chose to gain the pawn instead of a Rook.
The only move besides 35.Ke5?? d6#.
White retreats and puts strong pressure on me on his next moves.
I just want him to feel the same way as me when his knight annoyed me.
Because of 37...d5?! he took the chance to try and regain what he lost.
I ignored my attacked Rook...
and he did not take it.
40.Be3! was better.
Black is making it almost impossible for White to block.
I really didn't like this response. Better was 41.Bd3.
? There goes my Queen. The tables slightly turned away from me.
Threatenes 43.Rxf1 but the only sucess with this move is the start of my rook
Targeting the dark-square bishop.
I am creating unsucessful premature attacks.
Guarding the unguarded light-squared bishop.
Preventing 46.Bd4.
A critical pin!
Preventing 47.Nxd5.
White sucessfully tormented my Rook.
White has still not taken my defenceless Rook for a bishop.
? Wrong move. Full retreat was better.
!? I have two options 1) 50...a5 or 2) 50...Rxg6.
I take option two for granted.
?? Why didn't White do 51.Rg2?
White's Knight is completely gone!
I did not like this move though it was White's only available retreat.
The tides turn away from White.
Not bad but 53...Rg2! is better.
Not White's best move. 54.b5!? Rg2!.
! Found a way to include both rooks.
The endgame starts but it is not a draw.
White's failed opposition.
Okay for Black but better was 56...Rc4!.
White's best move at the time.
Best at move 56 but it is still helpful.
Abandoning the Rook would have killed my game.
! A move that taunts White to get my rook.
White has one pawn left; how is White going to use his pawn?
White is trying to get revenge on me.
White using impulsivenes realizes that he is not suceeding and stops checking me for a while.
A queen completely turns the tides however there is no rush.
White forgot about 72...Rb5b4.
One step closer to promotion. I am afraid that I'm having to much priority on my Rooks and I am required to sacrified one of them.
Started to chase the Rook around while having fun doing it with my king!
My only chance to fulfill the needed sacrifice.
White is completely hopeless reguardless of what he does.
Better was 78...Kd5! ending the game faster.
This is basically the end of White.
Run away White! Run away!!
I would have ended the game faster if I did the Staircase.
This game lasted two months and changed the way I played chess.
Standard queens gambit.
The Slav. I love playing both sides of this opening.
!? Not a good move not a bad move. Personally I like to develop my bishop to g5 on occasion and pin the f-knight but this doesn't look to be the time to accomplish that.
Developing piece number 2.
!? Again not bad but I was expecting the f-knight to pke it's head out by now.
Piece number 3 activated.
Dual threat. Not sure if this is the best way to recover the pawn but it does force my oppenent to lose a tempo to deal with the bishop.
? A meaningless pin. The first truly poor move of my opponent. Better in my opinion is Be6 securing the pawn for at least another move. Still only one piece developed...
Recapturing and developing piece #4.
Finally pulling the knight out. And I spy with my little 1320 rated eye...
Ne5! winning the bishop at a minimum with 8...e6 9.Ng4. Having to eye the Queen with the deepest lust and not being able to take the Queen is a terrible endeavor indeed.
?? What. Did my oppenent miss it completely?
# Pay attention especially if you are underdeveloped and your opponent has massed minor forces in the center
The English opening... [http://gameknot.com/analyze-board.pl?bd=15639050&fb=1&rnd=0.7226811586879194 <-- computer analysis]

A quick look at the database tell me that this isn't the usual way to deal with this opening - Nf6 and c5 are the two top options - but the win/loss ratio for Black isn't too significant so no harm done!

!? Simple development... apart from this move! I don't know whether Nf6 may have been better here but if I had played that it would have looked like a 'boring' Four Knights opening from my side of the board. Ne7 is passive but solid enough to be playable and there's always the g6 square to move to!
Opening up a line for the dark-squared bishop...
...while I tuck my king away to safety.
White pins my knight...
...and Black chases it off - though it weakens the light-squared diagonal to my king White can't do much with his light-squared bishop at the moment so it's not an immediate problem.
!? This is the start of a planned queenside pawn expansion - it was the only plan that I had here and it seemed like a reasonable one as well!
Meanwhile White continues development - he completes it by castling whereas I'd complete mine by developing my bishop.
Preparing a queenside thrust...

? and following through with it - though this turns out to be a mistake that was not exploited! White can exchange pawns then win one with Nxb5 because if Black plays Rxb5 then the discovered attack d4! wins back the material.
? Fortunately for Black White doesn't see this [and won't for the next couple of moves] and instead inhibits an advance to b4.
Black meanwhile lashes out in the centre.
White stakes his own claim to queenside...
...but I simply land my bishop on the d4 square now an outpost.
?! White shouldn't have exchanged here - my bishop wasn't threatening anything for one thing. Also Black gets to recapture with his knight and therefore can claim a strong outpost...

?! Though I fall victim to a bit of 'chess blindness' here. For some reason I didn't see that the knight could capture on d5 and thought that the knight would be confined to either a2 or b1 and that I'd create a nice passed pawn after dxe4. Though this was inferior to the knight capture it helped set up the foundation for the fireworks later on
After a bit of exchanges White relocates his bishop with tempo.
White's forces have mobilised quickly and are better co-ordinated; he definitely has the advantage at this point!
Bb7 is another option but this move forces White to react; he won't want doubled pawns!
The only reasonable move

The intention here is pretty clear; Rfc1 to pressure the c7 pawn. The best way to defend this pawn would be a rook to c8 [there's also c6 but it restricts my bishop]. However Black has something else in mind...
Setting up a dynamic reply in case Rfc1 is played...can you see it?

!? Here it is! This protects the c7 pawn by cutting off communication between the rooks as well as attacking both undefended bishops! It certainly complicates matters but incredibly GK analysis judges the position to be dead equal!
! Pretty much forced for White - trading the knight for the e2 bishop which allows a rook on the seventh rank and a dangerous passed pawn isn't at all recommended!

? Black stays aggressive knowing that taking the a3 pawn will result in the knight being trapped... but unfortunately after 23.Bg4! followed by 24.Qc2 the knight is still trapped! Gameknot's recommended continutation (23...f5 24.Bxf5 Qxf5 25.Rxf5 Nxd1 26. Rxd1) leaves Black a pawn down. Nxd2 was better here...

? I had expected White to play Qf1 but he surprises me with this move. I had a long think about what to do here - I saw pretty quickly how Black could win material but was unsure of the position that resulted from it. I explored a few other options including GK's recommended Qe6 but all options left Black a pawn down [with Qe6 Black would have a superior position but I didn't see it at the time]
! This is what wins the material - only one point up but still an advantage!

Despite the material advantage I wasn't too comfortable with the position that I had... the main concern being the fact that White had the bishop pair on an open board - I remember a certain Master player on here told me once that two bishops can sometimes be more powerful than a queen!
?! Preparing to double up on the e-file but analysis preferred Bc8 here relieving the b8 rook of its defensive duties.
Pushing away the rook...
...and advancing his king - White also had Bg4 driving the rook off the e-file altogether. If that had happened Black would probably have played Rc6.
Bishop centralisation but the fact that it's undefended makes it a target very shortly...
Once again GK analysis judges the position to be perfectly equal!
Doubling up on the e-file...

...but now it looks like Black's in a bind here! As both the bishop and pawn is attacked it looks like that pawn will fall. If 29...Bc6?? 30.f5! Rd6 31.Bf4 and the bishop falls. There was however a way to preserve the pawn...

? but this wasn't it! I was thinking of the counter-attack Bb1 after White snaps off the pawn but then White has Rd5 winning the d5 pawn. I didn't realise that until after I played the move. Better for Black was 29...Bb3! which maintains the material balance since Black has Re2+ if White captures on b3. If White retreats the bishop instead then Black has time to defend the pawn with Ba4.
Black is losing but he makes a few threats anyway to see if he can get anything out of the position.
I was expecting Bc1 but this works better...
Nothing will come out of Bb1 so Black threatens Bd7 instead - White prevents the loss of a pawn with Ra5 but after the exchange White's passed pawns diminish in power.
Nothin' doing!
Black doesn't want White to play f5 to drive away the bishop.
?? This is what Black was waiting for - White blunders! He is counting on the discovered attack on the e8 rook but leaves the g4 pawn hanging...
...and White needs to deal with the threat of Re2+
The White king drives away the bishop...

! but Black has no problem relocating it - here was another flaw in White's plan that could have but wasn't ruinous. The bishop on a4 is hanging and the rook now needs to move to avoid capture. Though White can't defend his bishop...
! he can take advantage of one of my hanging pieces. White has contained the damage but Black now holds the advantage.

Gameknot preferred Re7... citing the continuation Ba4! White remains a piece down but has strong counterplay because of his connected passed pawns. I don't know what the alternate rook move does to make this move invalid however...
White doesn't see that possibility and completes the exchange.

White offers a pawn - now there's something I wrote on my profile - 'If my opponent has 'given up' material it's probably not a blunder - there has to be a reason why he'd be willing to let the material go.'
?? I should check out my own profile more often! That pawn was laced with highly poisonous substances and taking it has just ruined Black's game! Rb7 would maintain the advantage.
!! White suddenly threatens to promote his pawn with Bc7 then b7. This makes Black's next move forced...
But now Black's rook has been cut off from the rest of the game!
Black's only active piece now is the king...
...but that's tied down too!

It's a matter of pawn pushing now but no matter how Black plays he will end up in Zugzwang. the king will have to move away from the f5 square the pawn will be captured and White can then proceed to move the king over to c6 to win the rook. There is no defence to this so I resign after my next move. Good game White!
Rather than form an ideal center by recapturing the Pawn White presses forward.
The Cardinal naturally prefers a Bishop to a Knight.
Now it is in fact *Black* who has a strong Pawn center.
Aiming after capturing the obstructing Pawn at the future home of the White King.
Leaving White nearly undeveloped.
Pressuring KB2.
Forced to guard the KBP.
Black has four pieces now trained on the denuded White K-side.
Removing the Q from the defense of the imperiled K-side.
Setting a trap...
...which White falls into. Now the Q is cut off entirely from the scene of action.
The riposte is swift.
The King is now exposed to the fury of the Cardinal's pieces.
Forcing the pace.
Forced [17 K-B3??? Q-N5 mate!]
Excellent utilization of a Bishop by the Cardinal.
Forced.
With mate to follow.
The only legal move allowing...
...this delightful finish.
A pretty standard opening
This forced me into capturing the knight or falling back d6
I capture to force white to double pawns and I gain a tempo
Opens up the possibility of c5 to allow the light squared bishop to develop but also blocks in dark squared bishop
Trying to open up the position
Fork Bishop and queen
Prevents d5
Looking to trade queens with 14. Qxf3 Qxf3 15.gxf3
With no other attacking piece My attack falters and so try and weaken the strong center of white
Wanting to play  18. d5 to open up  steamroller attack with the b2 bishop and g1 Rook
Doubling the rooks
Trying to control the b or d file
Prevents the Qxe6
Trying to keep queen to protect the bishop
Now I control the e-file trying to make some sort of an attack
Wanting to get rid of the bishop
Blocking in the pawn and trying to release the pressure on my king
Trying to force  a draw
I had realised the game was lost when I played Qh5 and saw the checkmate combo. I should have capture the pawn on f5
I enjoy playing Najdorf and Dragon and so started with Sicilian
I had never seen this and expected 3.Qf3 and so just played a normal Sicilian move 2... d6
This had me at a lost why would someone sacrifice their Bishop so early and I saw no future threats that couldn't be dealt with easily
Not 5...Be6 6. Qxb7 Nd7 losing me a pawn
Wanting to play 9.Nf7 winning a rook the rook on h8
A good move attacking and defending at the same time
Still controling the a2-g8 diagonal

Not 10.f4 attacking the e5 knight and defending the pawn
However 10... Bxg5 11.fxg5 Nxe4 wins a pawn
But with 12. d3 forces the e4 knight in Zugzwang
This was a interesting move as it allowed me to attack his Queen again
Pins the bishop
I was willing to trade queens because I was up a minor piece
Wanting to trade bishops
I decide to free up the bishop by trying to trade Night for Bishop He kindly accepts
Trying to push home my material advantage
He continues to accept my exchanges
Now the endgame begins
I look to attack his a-b pawn island
He gladly allows me to attack his pawn island because of 37. Rb7 and 38. a4
I realise I can win by taking the a and b pawns and then trading rooks so I take his f-pawn
Protect both pawns
He allows me to move free my a-pawn by attacking his two b pawns
Wants to free his own h pawn
Time to get the king involved
Now I can win easily by checking him and forcing him to move his h-pawn into my bishops path
He resigns here because of next combo
Now I have my a-pawn free to queen and my unmoved e-pawn able to queen if I need it
I played 2. d4 expecting 2... d5 french defence
Unexpected probably trying to play scholars mate but I was wary as this was my first game on the website
3. Nf3 so I could play
4. Bg5  was better as it forced 4...Qg6
This was what I expected to be played and prepared to take the Knight on h6 and open up the king side and prevent him castling or his king would be exposed

We both prepared to fianchetto on the h1-a8 diagonal. However my 8. g3 also stopped the Rook from capturing the g-pawn I if decided to develop to d3 or c4 or if Nc6 was played I could play Bb5 and stop him from moving his d-pawn otherwise he would be pinned
?? I played this aiming to fork the King and rook but I forgot about 10... Qb4+ 11. c3 Qxb5
Aiming to capture the h-pawn. Black defended while still controlling the half open g file
?! After I had played 14.Rg1?? Why not Bxf3 go up by 6

After opening up the King side for an attack at a later date I lost the ability to castle by playing Kf1 planning on hand castling. 19.Be4 was also possible but led to counterattacking chances and causing the Queen to be stuck guarding the bishop. Also 19.Be4 Bh6 stops the ability to castle Queen side which would have been the point of playing 19. Be4 so I could play 20. O-O-O
?! I thought of trading bishops so I could hand castle safely but after thought I realised if 20... Bxd3 2. Qxd3 I would been still down three and lose one of my main attacking pieces.
Instead b5 was played which was a dubious move weakening the fianchetto formation and creating a backwards a-pawn and an isolated b-pawn it also cut of the a6-f1 diagonal.
I wanted to remove the Black's ability to castle into his strongly protected queen side and I could do this thanks to 20... b5
Not the expected Kd8 hand castling although this may have been a better move considering I didn't have a dark squared bishop and allowed his a8 Rook to get involved.
I planned on removing the E rook so I could strengthen my center
I had conceived if a combo and thought I was down by three and should try it out

I needed to remove the Black queen of the 5th row so I could play Qxe5+  Kd8 Qe8#

I thought he would look to try and attack my rook with 26... cxb2 27. Rb1 Qb5 28. a4 Qb4 29.Qxe5+ Kd8 30. Qe8#
This threw a spanner in the works as I didn't think about this as I believed he would focus on his isolated pawn on c3
Next move my combination came into play
Yes from a very bad Position I had stolen a victory

Hi everyone!

This game had echos of my previous game against Master Janet in which she gave me an exchange sac in the middle game and later on Henry got caught in a mating net on the d column.  A similar thing happens in this game only this time just like the times Steve Backshall managed to evade the bees hippos and alligators (taking photos at the same time!) and get back to the truck Henry manages to escape from the clutches of the Wicked Witch and find sanctuary on the a column.  I end up being a whole rook up and with Bob's mating attack completely burnt out it was only a matter of time before I forced a queen swap and ensured safe passage for a pawn to get to Glendadom before Bob waved the white flag.  So how did this happen?  Well you can follow the action by the Gameknot Analysis link below.  http://gameknot.com/analyze-board.pl?bd=15462595&fb=1&rnd=0.16887384178856135
2. .... dxc4 - after Bob starts with a Q pawn opening I decided to play the QGA as it gives me more open play and I feel a little less vulnerable to passivitis.
4. a4 - to interfere with b5 - if b5 then PxP and my a6 pawn cannot recapture due to the fact it is pinned against my a8 rook.
5. .... Na5 - with the possibility of putting a knight in on b3.  As is now my steed backs up my extra pawn on c4.
7. ...... e6 - opens up the a3-f8 diagonal for Fou Lenoir.
10. Qxa1 - and here we have another exchange sac.  Will this one work?  Only time will tell.
12. ..... Nd5 - I must counter in the centre to completely avoid being over-run.
15. Bd3 - quite a few exchanges here but white could have a very dangerous attack going against Henry even though Bob has castled on the same wing.
15. ..... Qf6 - so out comes Glenda the Defender!
16. Qc2 - ouch - my c7 pawn and my h7 pawns are both en prise.  I do not want the Wicked Witch of the West deep into my position so it will have to be the h7 pawn to jettison.
19. ...... Kg8 - as Bob's mating attack gathers pace Henry prepares for a Deadly Dash towards the queenside.
20. ...... Rd8 - my rook gives Henry the room to do so.
23. ...... Kf8 - and so the race against time is on.  Can Henry make it?  Only time will tell.
25. .... Ke7 - Bob has given up his knight for the f7 pawn but has he overreached himself?  Maybe.
27. Qh7+ - Henry will get out of check by going to d8 but is he safe there?

29. Qxg8+ - Henry must leg it again as much as his tired old body will allow - thank god his partiality to a seafood diet has kept him fit.  Also Bob only has his queen and lsb to get hold of Henry so it looks as if he will get his much needed sanctuary.
30. ...... Kb6 - made it!

31...... Qb4 - at last Glenda defends her other half aaaaah!  She is also thinking about obtaining more p(r)awns for Henry's table tonight - there are two really juicy ones on a4 and b2 and she is mentally compiling a list of ingredients for a p(r)awn seafood mornay!  Can you see something else that Glenda is also eyeing up and do you see a dark dark shadow of that Chessic Grim Reaper hanging over Bob's king?  If so on what square is he about to descend?
32. h3 - to create an escape square for his king but now Glenda just starts gathering in those p(r)awns!
33. ..... Qb3 - forking two pawns.
35. Qc7+ - because my pieces inter-defend one another this check is merely a spite check.
36. ...... Bf5 - on MOVE 36 I finally complete my queenside development.
37. ..... Be4 - after the Wicked Witch turned my weakie pawn on f6 into dust I have designs on the g2 square.
38. ..... Qc2 - trying to force an exchange of queens.

39. ..... Qxg2+ - Bob tries to duck the exchange but I exchange anyway even though Fou Leblanc will be given up for the g2 pawn.  This leaves Bob with just his king and bishop and three pawns.  I have a rook and four pawns at my disposal.  White is lost and can only try for a stalemate.
41. ..... Kb4 - Henry now makes way for my a pawn to proceed to Glendadom.

43. .... a4 - the best Bob can do is give up his bishop for my a pawn but I have my b pawn who will get to Glendadom instead.  Meanwhile my rook will prevent a white pawn from ever going to the 8th rank.

45. .... a2 - just one move away from Glendadom but Bob now waves the white flag.  Commiserations Bob you gave me a terrible scare in the middlegame but somehow Henry escaped and I am just sooooo relieved.  Coach Ion and Gameknot analysis will not hesitate to point out just how Henry managed to get away!
The Ruy Lopez in a much more standard defensive configuration than Bird's Defence. But Bird handles things with aplomb.
The game has become very open. Bird is now preparing to Castle after which he will attempt to mount an attack.
With only 2 pieces in play Bird now mounts a spectacular attack with the aid of a couple of Pawns. You'd think it would be defensible but he makes it work!
Bird is too alert to fall into 11 P(either one)xN??? B-B4! winning the Q.
Steinitz pounces on the Rook but he leaves his King defenseless and his position undeveloped.
Forcing the Bishop to move away from the King file.
Delaying Bird one move.
A very safe haven. Steinitz's King by contrast is in grave danger.
A useless move. Steinitz should have at least taken the chance to Castle. It probably wouldn't have helped much but he could drag out his resistance some.
Forcing the action. If Steinitz tries 14... BPxP Bird has 15 QxKP ch K-B1 16 PxP ch KxP 17 B-R6 mate!
14... O-O may have been marginally better but the position is hopeless in any case.
Bird misses the spectacular finishing line 15 PxQP dbl ch K-B1 16 Q-K8 ch QxQ 17 PxQ (Q) mate! However he hunts down Steinitz's King quickly enough.
Forced else 16 QxR is decisive.
Opening the King file to deadly effect.
16... KxP is equally bad [17 PxP dis ch.]
Aiming down the mighty open file.
Delays mate by one move.
The final blow.
Forced.
Finis. Bird tied Steinitz's position into knots.

Hi everyone!

Has anybody ever heard of Steve Backshall?  Well he is a guy who just lurves chasing wild animals although on occasions they chase him.  I found out about him from watching a Children's programme called CBBC with my six year old Charlotte and later played the CBBC game where Steve has to outrun bees hippos and alligators - this game is called Steve's Deadly Dash.  In this MT in aid of the Christchurch Earthquake I am playing Master Janet.  Things seemed to be OK for me when suddenly Henry was subjected to a deadly dash from her rook and the Wicked Witch of the West.  Alas Henry got caught and he had to rest up!  Anyhow on with the game.  Gameknot Analysis is provided in the following link.http://gameknot.com/analyze-board.pl?bd=15488483&fb=1&rnd=0.19786173690656117.  Janet kicks off with the English Opening - 1.c4.
2. g3 - white usually likes to fianchetto a lsb on the kingside in the English Opening and Janet is no exception.
4. ....... Nxd5 - pawn trade.
7. ...... Be7 - clearing the way for kingside castling.
9. b4 - a queenside pawn storm perhaps?
11. ..... Nd4 - an interesting passage of play is about to evolve.  The e5 pawn is left to hang but ....
15. Qxa1 - ..... but there is an exchange sac on white's part.  Can this be justified?  We shall see.
17. ..... Re8 - my rook is en prise and must move to the only possible square.
19. Bd4 - a line up on the a1-h8 diagonal could spell danger for Henry.
21. .... Bh3 - wanting to exchange off white's strong lsb.  Unfortunately white's dsb is the one I should perhaps be thinking of ridding myself of.

24. e4 - puts the question to my knight.  I opt for f6 - will Janet be prepared to part with this strong bishop in order to open up the g column?  Will this decision prove costly to me?  Time will tell.

26. Qxf6 - Aha here is the Wicked Witch and my f7 pawn is en prise.  I choose to defend by Qh5?? but this proves to be the losing move according to Gameknot Analysis.  My opponent also suggested 26.Qe6 and she thought that if I played that then I would have had great drawing chances.  Again I miss the chance to add Janet's name to my Master Draw list!
28. ..... Qb3 - I eschew the knight on a4 because Henry will cop Old Matey if Glenda takes it.  Instead she defends the pawn on f7.  However Rg5+ proves decisive and now comes Henry's Deadly Dash.
32. Qc6+.  Here I resign on the grounds of Unavoidable Mate.  Henry has only one square (d8) and next move comes Qxe1#.  Well played Janet.  Joanne
This is the second game I want to show from our Gruenfeld mini-tournament (the first was my loss to "superpom") and again the d-pawn is decisive. Fortunately I have the White pieces this time.
A small mistake - and even right out of the opening. Thematic is c7-c5 to challenge the White center.
Wrong square for the Knight! 11. - Nc6 would still give White a slight plus but now the b7 pawn can be taken for free. After 11. - Nc6 12. Be3 The pawn could be protected by 12. - Na5.
And the d-pawn is on its way again ...

Let us stop and make some status: Black has lost the Bishop pair (not un-important in an open game like the Gruenfeld) has lost a pawn and the Bg7 looks very passive. White will put pressure on the isolated a- and c-pawns protect the passed pawn on d5 with Rd1 and get the two Bishops to better placements. Frankly I hate to play Black in this opening line but of course it is just a matter of taste.
Black cannot do much more than defend in this position.
A glimpse of hope! If Black can get the Knight to the perfect blocking square d6 the lifejacket has almost healed completely.
Of course White will not allow it and now the d-pawn causes havoc once again. Roughly speaking Black is lost already.

A funny move. Bg4 dxc4 and e6 are the normal moves in this position. I don't really understand what the bishop is supposed to be doing on d7.

Not a good idea at all. the dxc4 lines are the only heavily theoretical lines in the Reti Slav and Bd7 is not a good move it belongs on e6 in most lines or if not the queen needs access to d5 so white definately has an edge now in a position which can at the best of times need accurate play from Black

Qc2 is more normal in these lines (e.g. Nf3 d5 c4 c6 g3 Nf6 Bg2 dxc4 0-0 Nbd7 Qc2 would be mainline) but I felt that now the usual plans of defending the pawn with Be6 and Nd7b6 wont fly then I can afford to secure the position on the queenside play Na3 Qc2 win the pawn and have the better game.

This is a terrible move. Weakening the h1-a8 diagonal and not even holding the pawn. Things are even worse after a deep think though. The lines get a bit sharp but are worth looking at. The continuation will be axb5 cxb5 Nd4 after which Black can branch:

1. ... Bc6?! Naxb5 Qd7 (Qb6?? Ra6!) Nxc6 Nxc6 Nd4 with a lost position
2. ... Nc6 Naxb5 Qb7 Nxc6 Bxc6 Rxa7! Rxa7  (Bxg2 Rxb7 Bxb7 shouldn't give enough compensation for the queen) Nxa7 Qxa7 Bxc6+

There is no defence. Qxa6 obviously runs into Nc7+ Whilst all other queen moves drops the knight.
The last tactic to completely finish the game. Bxa8?? axb6 would have given some slight compensation though insufficient but the played move forces resignation.

This position was the stipulation of the thematic mini-tournament which cavalcanti conceived. The King's gambit accepted or also known as the King's Knight's gambit.
This is "book" according to the computer analysis. I do not know much about it....my play is from common sense and out of my admiration of the earliest masters. Capablanca and the like.

Still book but let me say that my opponent seems to want an accelerated development. So then I consider here and now that my opening shall become closed and attempt to neutralize all range of movement which his pieces may initially acquire.

So now the reasoning begins and the book gets chucked out the window........so says the analytic computer(not me!) The e7 bishop is set to assist only with my king side pawn majority the move played therefor establishes the queen side bishop to be the most mobile!
My opponent chooses the exact thought which I expressed earlier....development development development. He builds a strong central and strategical position which I will attempt to dismiss.
His king knight is now limited to 2 out of 8 possible moves and begins the advance of the majority.
Staying in theme and protecting the king to the side which I should have difficulties projecting my own pieces.
Attempting three things... 1. developing.  2. central governance. 3. future attempt at restriction of the bishops range.
Good developing move perhaps planning central expansion.

Tho most would refrain from moving pieces twice so early in the game due to getting behind in development I set the standard of my opening to be a restrictive one(to the opponent) and will adhere to that goal. In addition to deeming the opening theme a failure if I deviate from my intentions.
Was attacked and now is in a cramped position.
More so a need for developing while toying with 0-0-0 in the future plus enjoying some spacial benefits.
Oops his theme changed first! Now his wishes may be in the restriction of my space!
I'll keep the pin and reduce his central dominance.

So much for the pin but where is his opening theme? Shifted from rapid development to a quick attempt to control e5? Hey I'm not a master but please stick to your guns as much as possible at best to lessen the confusion of the upcoming middle game.
This was done at this time to benefit the center and to lessen range that the knight may utilize.
Here comes the new shift from deployment to central aggression.
In keeping with my continuous blockade theme and making the queen side like a BP oil slick! Needing removal and repositioning.
This is where I saw the chance to rid myself of a doubled pawn and seek compensation for the weaknesses in whites king side.
So take it I did!
The move allowed time to return to the attack of center and develop plus g5 is suspect.

I kinda played this in a panic....not really analyzing the potential pin rook to g8 may present and finally taking my first step from playing the Python to troop movement but figured that it had to be near the area of transition to the middle game so why not do it!

Paul Keres is a name that I recognised but this is the first time that I've looked at any of his games... and after looking at this one and learning a little more about him I think I'll be checking out more of his games! (Fun fact; he is the only player to have beaten nine undisputed world champions!) As far as I'm aware this isn't one of his more famous games but definitely one to check out!
The modern Steinitz defence according to Gameknot's database...
...and now it's the Noah's Ark trap - pretty ironic that it aids Black when it is White who played the move to start it! This trap is sprung...
...first by driving back White's bishop...
...then by exchanging on d4.
Should White take the pawn here?

[8.Qxd4 is a blunder that allows the Noah's Ark trap: 8...c5 and ...c4 trapping the White bishop] (!) Nope - Hort doesn't fall for the trap and instead ensures the win of the pawn - Keres has to answer the threat to his rook.

Obviously Hort reckons that his Bishop is a target so he aims to exchange it off. However it looks like an extreme loss of tempo when a bishop that has already moved five times (soon six) has to be exchanged off for one that will only have moved once! White could still play 9.Qxd4 here but would need to play a3 to have an escape hole for his bishop (9...Bd7 or 9...Ne7 and the Noah's Ark trap is renewed with c6 c5 and c4)
Equalising in material - a centralised queen is great when it can't be driven back but Keres could play c5 with tempo later if he wanted to.

[White's centre is slightly weak and he can't stop Black's queenside expansion so White is slightly worse already] - The development of both sides is nearing their ends and Keres already has a plan queenside. Hort's counterplay will have to either come in the centre or kingside if he can't stop operations queenside.
Possibly hoping that Keres would exchange here maybe? a3 was another move that could be played but after 14...a5 the pawn will still reach the b4 square. In this position b4 can easily be played...
!? But Keres delays it signalling a desire to open the d-file later on (he doesn't by the way - he never needs to!)
Why not axb5 I wonder? And on that note why play this move? The purpose escapes me here...
The b4 push comes now and Keres gains space queenside
Hort relocates his knight to an aggressive square - with the pressure that is building up queenside it won't do to be passive!
The b4 pawn didn't need protecting but Keres had to play this straight away to stop White from playing a5 himself!
Locking things up queenside. However Keres still has the initiative and uses it to improve the position of his bishop...
...like this; now it has control of the long dark-square diagonal with a gain of tempo as well!
! Keres continues his queenside attack with gusto; meanwhile Hort doesn't really have a lot of targets to exploit.

[if 20.dxc6 e.p. Qxc6 White's weakness at c2 is more significant than Black's at d6] - not only would c2 have been easier to attack it is an important base pawn for White whereas d6 would have been a weak isolated pawn

!? Interesting; Keres offers the bishop exchange. This isn't a move that would leap out on you while analysing the position but the point is that if Hort exchanges the d-pawn although passed would prove to be a liability that needs protection.
Refusing the exchange.

Consistent to Black's plan - his next move would be c4 and if White recaptures with the pawn (obviously not the queen; the point of Rbc8) Black simply takes on a4 to create two connected passed pawns.
The only move which can stop this
Keres now targets the pawn at c2 which is defended for now...
!? but Hort converts it to an exchange hoping to quell Black's queenside pressure.

[The game is already strategically decided. White has no reasonable defence to ...f5-f4 and in some cases onwards to f3] - I wonder what f4 would achieve here though - simply worsening the position of the bishop?
If Black plays f4 now then the White bishop has the f2 square to retreat to
! Cutting off access between the b1 rook and the b3 pawn - White has no way of saving it!
Nothing much Hort can do really so he improves the position of his queen while maintaining watch over the a4 pawn which is now passed...
...However Keres now has two! Furthermore Hort's bishop is under attack...

There was an attractive counter-attack that Hort could have tried but unfortunately it would not have worked out; 27.Bg5?! Rd7 28.Rf2 and it looks like the b2 bishop is won but then Keres has the simple 28...h6! and the bishop can't stay on the c1-h6 diagonal to prevent Qe3 (If Bc1 then Qd1+ followed by Bd4+ wins)
You know what they say about passed pawns!
White still looking for some sort of breakthrough with his queen - of course because of the bishop on b2 the a4 pawn is immune.
[Hereabouts Black starts to go astray. 28...Qa3 wins easily] - in other words Keres should have been more focused on pusing his passed pawns than chasing Hort's queen around.
After a bit of rook shuffling and queen chasing Keres now prepares to advance his pawns though perhaps Keene's earlier suggestion of Qa3 might have been better
Hort meanwhile creates a passed pawn of his own!
[White has real counterplay] - For example one of Hort's plan for his pawn could be d7 followed by Rfe1 followed by Qe8+ could be worth a shot!
Keres retreats his bishop for defence...

...but allows this move from Hort! Now wherever the queen moves the c4 pawn is ripe for the picking - has Keres lost his advantage? Well first take a second look at the title of this annotation then work out the one move that doesn't lose the c4 pawn... :)

[A remarkable queen sacrifice] (!!) I'd call it more than remarkable myself! But then again once you remember that quote that two connected passed pawns on the sixth rank is more powerful than a rook this move isn't that surprising!
Keres advances with full steam attacking the rook with tempo.
Now Keres threatens 38...c2!
Now Keres threatens 39...Ra1!
! The best chance for Hort at this point; if Keres played too quickly and tried Ra1 now then Qe8+ steals the game!
! Forced but powerful all the same - Keres eliminates his back rank weakness and does so with the right pawn - 39...g6?? allows Hort to draw with 40.Qe6!!
Hort presses ahead regardless still counting on Keres to slip up - 40...Rxe8?? 41.dxe8=Q+ Kh7 42.Qxa4
No deal - with the attack that he has Keres doesn't care about a lost rook...
Still Hort wants the one on a4 not the one on d8!
[Despite being a whole queen in arrears Black is winning here]
[If 43.Qc4 c2 44.Qf1 Rd5 45.Be3 cxb1=Q 46.Qxb1 Ra5 47.Kf2 Kg8 and ...Ra1 winning]
This move is forced to prevent both pawn promotion and Rd1+
The d1 square won't work so Keres' rook moves on to a better square. Thank god for the bishop on f6 from Black's point of view!
It won't be the c1 square...
Threatens b1=Q+ - but leaves the f5 pawn hanging! Hort can safely capture on f5 with check...
...but Hort doesn't take it - Given his level of play it's unlikely to be an oversight!
Keres defends his pawn... but this may have been what Hort had wanted. Not that he had a winning advantage just a last-ditch effort to secure the draw a bit later on...
Attacks the pawn again but also opens up an escape route for his king...
! In preparation for this move - now the only way to stop promotion is for Hort to sac his queen!
Preventing the queen from being pinned
Hort allows the re-arrival of the Black queen...
...in return for one last attack made possible by 46...g6.
If Hort can withstand an attack from Black then he steals the game... However Keres has things under control.
! A pawn sac to solidify Black's advantage - White has to take since Kh4 leads to mate after Qe1+
The queen exchange is forced and Hort resigned in a hopeless position - a spectacular game!

This game was very exciting. At each move I was looking forward to what my opponent would have done. I don't know if it is tactically brilliant; but it was exciting to explore the different tales which the chessboard could tell depending on each move.
The closed Sicilian is somehow not very popular. The Black can be comfortable and probably the best line is 2. Nf3 or 2. c3; but it's a very sharp and extremely entertaining opening.
Classic position.

I was more used to 9. Nd4 9. ... a6 and 9. ... Rb8. The point is probably to defend c5 in order to advance in d5 but the black must be careful with that diagonal. Seemingly this is a book move so I won't protest about that.

The queen might choose d2 however if the Black plays d5 he threatens d4 and one must think of a good position for the bishop. This might be d2. Moreover I can choose to play: 10. ... d5 11. exd5 exd5 12. Bd2 Re8 13. Rf2 Nf5 14. Re2.
Unexpected. The bishop leaves the diagonal unguarded to pin the d-pawn. I would have played 10. ... d5.

This might come somewhat unprepared especially because the Black is about to play d5 and then there will be less chances to attack on the side. However I needed a bit more space to maneuver and I played Qe1 to use the e1-h4 diagonal after all!
Is that fear I see in 11. ... f5? 11. ... d5 was to prefer.
Usually one takes with g. In this particular case however I couldn't wait to boast my bishop with a longer diagonal. The Nc6 is pinned.
I think that taking by e eliminates one weakness.
I have no interest in taking in f5 at the moment. e6 is a more attractive target. It has become *the* target.
Well this was truly unexpected. I thought the Nc6 was pinned.
The White shouts his skepticism to the Black's chances to checkmate before entering the endgame.
15. ... Nxc2 16. Qxe6+ Qxe6 17. Nxe6 Rxa8 18. Rc1 is just about the same but with some pieces swapping (not good for the Black).
Yes the 10th move wasn't that great.

The situation is getting complicated. It may be hard to believe but the square e1 must be available for the KING! The big threat of the Black now is Dc6-g2#. From g3 the Queen controls g2. However Qf2 which also controls g2 cannot be played since the Black would threaten mate in h1.
The Black spotted another weakness: the e2 square where the knight might fork the royal couple.

Kf2! I thought this move deserved an exclamation mark when I played. The computer does not agree and proposes:

18. gxf5 Ndxf5 19. Qg4 Bd4+ 20. Rf2 Ng6 21. Re1 Re8 22. Nce4 Rf8 23. a4 Bxf2+ 24. Nxf2 e5 25. axb5 exf4 26. Bxf4 Nxf4 27. Qxf4 Qxb5

I don't know. For the moment Kf2 solves the problem of the fork but even more importantly it prepares Rg1. Without a counterattack the Black is bound to open the lines and slaughter the white soldiers!

The computer is unhappy again: … h6 19. Nh3 Nf3 20. g5 hxg5 21. Be3 b4 22. Nd1 g4 23. Ng5 Nxg5 24. fxg5 Kf7 25. Bd2

The point of e5 is opening new lines. However this might have been more effectively prepared with Rf8.
You have to think that at each move the threats b4 Qc6 e5 d5 Rf8 must be accurately calculated... the risk is terribly high!
Pins the knight and poses an immediate threat to h7.
The knight has found a strong square. The most important feature of the e4 outpost is that the Black must fear Nxc5 threatening the Queen.
Activity! The white king is boldly walking around but two black pieces are pinned!

The computer suggests 23. Nb1 exf4 24. c3 bxc3 25. Bxc3 Kh8 26. Qg4 Be5 27. Na3 Qe6 28. Qg6 Qxa2 29. Bxd4 Bxd4+

but I don't see the advantage of pointing to a3...
Mabe this was too bold... 24. c3 was more precise -- but much less fun!! The white looks forward to freedom but now it will be hard...
I had only considered 24. ... d5 and 24. ... Be4 (which I thought the best for the Black). Anyway the Nf5 is free now. The threat is very simple: 24. ... Be4.
Nf5 blocked once again!
The Black feared the worst. However this was the time to open the lines with Bxe4. Now he will have to defend himself.
Better late than never.
This is retreat. Bxe4 was still better after all.
I actually feared 27. ... Ne5 to which I thought to reply 28. Bxe5 Nxe3+ (but also Qxe5) 29. Kxe3 Qxe5 threatening 30. ... d5.
All is lost for the Black.
After 29. … Nd4 30. Qxe6 Nxe6 31. Nxf7 Nxf4 the White is two qualities up anyway.
The White calls the last forces to arms.
32. ... Nxg7 33. Qxe3 Qxe3+ 34. Kxe3 was probably better.
The Black resigned. For me it was a very beautiful and rewarding game.

The first Sveshnikov I've had on Gameknot (my favourite opening) and it's been very much overdue

This isn't a move I've had before making me think that it is indeed simply the loss of a pawn

(after checking this over with chessbase after the match Bd2 scores 8.7% for White from 23 games not exactly inspiring)
If instead Bxe5 then Nxe5 Qe2 0-0 Qxe4 Re8 leaves White caught in a horrible discovered attack
Black's knight looks a bit funny but actually fights for the centre quite well. The only problem will be developing the light-squared bishop which is worth a pawn and the centre and then some

9/10 times castling quenside is a way to get butchered in the Sveshnikov and this proves to be no exception. Normally the bishop on e6 is a factor into this but really the Black control of the centre means that he is the only one who can ever realistically build up a successful attack

It looks a bit risky to play this move with the mate themes on g7 and lack of a dark-squared bishop but the Black pieces make it very hard for White Queen to approach and the dark-squared bishop is frozen out by the centre pawns. The only way White can utilise the advanced h pawn to his advantage will be to get the f pawn in support or break up the centre which there wont be time to do

Qe2 had been the expected move but g3 is fine as well. In this sort of position if a side is making defensive moves they are normally struggling but the key point is that Black can make these moves without conceding tempo. For example Bd7 forced White to take action concerning the attack on c3 and now Qc7 makes White go on the defensive without building up his attack at the same time. This all comes from Black's pieces being better placed and coordinated to combine attack and defense

QxBc6 but that's just a trade of the Queen for the Bishop resulting in 23. QxQc6+ After that Black's King has virtually no place to go because he's then trapped on the home rank. At this point Black resigned.
c4 is an alternative taking play into a Gurgenidze Accelerated Dragon after g6. Nc3 is fine though expecting a Classical Sicilian
This is quite an odd move order for the dragon but I couldn't find a punishment of any kind
Bb3 isn't necessary due to the early d6. We are now in a normal dragon as opposed to an accelerated
This is more precise than the usual Bb3. It looks odd to retreat the bishop but the knight doesn't belong on a5 so it will likely transpose to a more mainstream dragon line after Bd7 Rc8 and Nc4.

A surprising move and not one I particularly rate. The bishop itself may not have gained anything by going to e2 but at least the a1 rook can swing into the attack faster if necessary afetr 0-0-0 so I don't see how Black has gained anything.

A surprising move and not one I particularly rate. The bishop itself may not have gained anything by going to e2 but at least the a1 rook can swing into the attack faster if necessary after 0-0-0 so I don't see how Black has gained anything.

This doesn't seem consistent. The only meaningful idea behind Nc6 I thought was to play into a 0-0-0 rather than a Bc4 dragon with d5 where the loss of tempo may be made slightly relevant by the fact that I'm in an opening less consistent with my repertoire.

The last two moves have resulted in a transposition to mainline Qa5 dragon with an extra tempo spent on Be2. Now after the main move h5 then g4 will come with more force now thanks to the bishop on e2 and the rook on d1 getting to g1 quickly
This is just a weird move. It's very rare that Black can be thinking about positional movement on the kingside in a dragon without the attack breaking through

This move is another strange one to look at. It has a few interesting lines though. The main sequence I looked at was f4 Bxc3 bxc3 (Qxc3 Nxe2 Rxe2 Bxg4) Nxe2 Qxe2 where white does have the doubled pawn weakness but this wont be significant because of the dark square weaknesses in Black's kingside and fact that White's queenside is much more developed.
This makes Black's position inconsolable. The losses of tempo are quite visible with the four pawns on the kingside compared to Black's immobile a and b pawns.
Nc5 looks nice but sadly doesn't actually do anything after Qd8
The attack now breaks through
not helping matters by opening the g file
White's threats aren't subtle but they force Black's responses. When you're making defensive moves in the dragon without getting initiative it's a good sign that your position is lost.
And the finish now is the rather good looking:

With Rxg7 Nxf6+ Kh8 Rxg7 Kxg7 Nxd7 Bxd7 Bd4 being game over. Sorry about a lack of analysis in this game it was more based on opening themes than concrete variations as the attacking moves are quite easy to find and the position sort of plays itself
I now have complete control of the four most important squares on the board. (Not a win but a step toward it!)
I castle as a precaution before I make any attack.
White is not comfortable with my bishop on c5!    He also wants to build a nice pawn defense on his queen side.
Back step!
White sees my threatening rook and moves b5 instead of taking my pawn on a5. (A reasonable move!)
White looks for a way to get his horse on b6 with hopes of taking my bishop or rook forcefully. He must first divert my bishop on c5 first though.
White had planned to use his pawn on b5 to be the distraction but....
...that is all to change!
White dumps his past plans and tries some other tactic.
I repel him.
Retreat? No attack. By taking my knight on f6 he would force me to use my pawn defense to take him which is meant for guarding my king and thus open a weak spot for a future checkmate!
So I back him up!
Well I'm going to try something different to my advantage.
Check! A forced move is made by White!
His rook is in peril and so he is once again forced to move.
Sacrifices have to be made during a game in order to gain a more advantages position.
Ah! that was excellent!
I will now sacrificing my queen because I have the better position. He is now almost helpless to checkmate me without sacrificing of many valuable pieces!
Now for an attack!
Hmmm he is going to regret that move!
He is down a bishop. What he fails to realize is that his fully exposed king gives me the odds of winning. It is to late to sacrifice pieces now he needs to get his king to a more protected spot!
To late!
The white rook is forced into a worse position.
The white horse is totaled!
The white king is on the run now.....
...heading for what looks like a safe place but....
....it's more like a trap!
Adios mate!

CHECKMATE!

The most important losing factor for white was that he did not keep his king covered. It cannot be stressed enough! The most important piece is NOT the queen But....the king! It must be given #1 priority in our strategies!
